            Melanie Cataldo, Office hours Mon/Wed by appointment
            <url href="mailto:mcataldo3@framingham.edu">mcataldo3@framingham.edu</url> 
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Class meets</title>
          <p>
            Monday/Wednesday, May Hall 407
            8:30-11:20 am
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Always bring to Class</title>
          <p>
            Materials pack &amp; Self
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Course Description</title>
          <p>
            An examination of the language of visual communication, focusing on the principles of design.
            Students explore line, shape, form, value, texture, color, and space in relation to various
            compositional strategies. Lecture and discussion sessions introduce historical and contemporary
            theories of two-dimensional design.  
          </p>
        </li>

      </dl>

    <!-- Use paragraphs to break apart subsections -->
    <paragraphs>
      <title>NACE Core Competencies</title>

      <p>
        Ask employers what they want from new graduates, and communication tops the list. The NACE competencies spotlight the tools current students need to find work in an ever changing job market.
        Color and Design asks students to consistently practice the following competencies: 
      </p>
        <p>
          • Communication - Understand the importance of and demonstrate verbal, written, and non-verbal/body language, abilities.
          Employ active listening, persuasion, and influencing skills
        </p>
         <p>
        • self development- Show an awareness of own strengths and areas for development.
Identify areas for continual growth while pursuing and applying feedback. 
         </p>
         <p>
        • critical thinking - Multi-task well in a fast-paced environment
         </p>
        <p>
         • professionalism - Maintain a positive personal brand in alignment with organization and personal career values.
        Be present and prepared.Demonstrate dependability (e.g., report consistently for work or meetings). Prioritize and complete tasks to accomplish organizational goals
      </p>
      <p>
        <url href="https://www.naceweb.org/career-readiness/competencies/career-readiness-defined/#competencies">The 8 NACE Core Competencies</url>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <!-- Other subsections for larger dividers -->
   <subsection xml:id="sec-assessments">
    <title>Grading</title>

      <p>
        You will be graded based on your effort and progress over the time of the course. You will
        receive a grade for each project and assignment. Any project can be reworked and turned in
       later in the semester for an improved grade.
       • 35%: participation - attendance, class discussion, working during class time, initiative,
       communication with professor and peers
       • 35%: process - depth of exploration, concepts, experimentation
       • 30%: presentation - quality of final projects and assignments
      </p>
    </subsection>
     
  <subsection xml:id="sec-structure">
    <title>Class Structure</title>

    <p>
      1. a visual introduction to relevant works
      2. project introduction and warm-up activity
      3. work on project
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sec-topics">
    <title>Project topics</title>
    <p>
     Making what you see,
    </p>
    <p>
     Shape and color,
    </p>
    <p> 
    Visual Movement,
     Contrast and Balance,
     Creating Depth,
     Storytelling images
    </p>
  </subsection>
    
  <subsection xml:id="sec-attend">
    <title>Attendance</title>
    <p>
    Please attend class. This is a studio class. Class begins promptly at 8:30 AM. Arriving late or 
    leaving early is disruptive and will affect your grade. If you have an emergency or you are
    sick, please email me before the beginning of class. If I don’t hear from you, you will not
    receive instructions.
    </p>
    <p>
    • 4 absences before mid semester will result in a failing grade for the course
    • 4 absences over the semester will result in one full grade drop from your FINAL course grade (for example: from a ‘B’ to a ‘C’).
    • 6 absences will result in a failing grade for the course
    </p>
    <p>
    The information in this syllabus is subject to change. Students will be notified of changes.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sec-policies">
    <title>Framingham State Policies and Services</title>
    <p>
    Academic Services
    The Center for Academic Success and Achievement, or CASA, offers professional and peer
    tutoring, academic success coaching, and disability resources and accommodations. CASA
    is also home to GenerationOne, an affinity group for first-generation college students as
    well as community outreach and mentor-ship programs. CASA is open to all current students.
    </p>
    <p>
    Academic Misconduct
    All students in attendance at Framingham State University are expected to be honorable
    and to observe standards of conduct appropriate to a community of scholars. The Institution
    expects from its students a higher standard of conduct than the minimum required to avoid
    discipline. Academic misconduct includes all acts of dishonesty in any academically related
    matter and any knowing or intentional help or attempt to help, or conspiracy to help,
    another student. The university policy regarding academic honesty will be followed in the
    event of academic misconduct. (*See Framingham State University Undergraduate Catalog).
    </p>
    <p>
    Security/Safety/Responsibility
    The computers are for students enrolled in graphic design courses. Printing in the computer
    lab is for graphic design only (for example, please do not print a 150 page history book
    PDF). Please do not be careless with or waste paper and ink in the lab. Framingham State
    University and the Department of Art and Music are not responsible for student work and/or
    personal belongings left unsecured in classrooms. Lockers and storage facilities are available
    for use during the semester for students enrolled in this course. Please be aware that open
    shelving is used at your own risk. Students should be particularly mindful of leaving new
    material out at the beginning and end of the semester.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
